popped and one company after another imploded fueling an internet sector freefall that lasted for the next two and a half years businesses and investors were forced to acknowledge that venture capital and initial public offerings did not guarantee income or make up for the lack of sound business plans with the spectacular rise and subsequent crash of many of these dotcom companies few were left standing after the dust had settled for related reading see  steps of a bubble amazoncom nasdaqamznfounded by jeff bezos in  amazon is the largest online retailer in the world in  amazon made its online debut as a bookstore eventually adding movies music electronics computer software and many other consumer goods to its diversified offerings amazons initial public offering took place on may   at a price of  per share rising to more than  and subsequently dropping to less than  after the bubble burst like other dotcoms amazons business plan focused more on brand recognition and less on income and it did not turn a profit until the fourth quarter of  today amazon trades at over  per share and employs more than  people with reported net sales of  billion the initial valuation of an ipo can determine the success or failure of a specific stock but how is that price determined for more see how an ipo is valued ebay nasdaqebayfounded by pierre omidyar in  ebay is a popular online auction and retail presence ebay showed extraordinary growth early on as the number of hosted auctions flew from  during  to  million during just the first month of  on september   ebay went public at an ipo price of  prices had no trouble topping  on the first day of trading ebay expanded its product categories to include practically anything that can sell  from antiques and gold coins to automobiles and real estate  and also incorporated different more popular types of auctions these moves proved successful for ebay which now has more than  employees with reported revenues topping  billion for related rea